.TH LIVE-KERNEL-UPDATER 1 "2026-05-21" "Version 26.05.2" "antiX/MX Documentation"
.nh
.ad l
.SH NAME
live\-kernel\-updater \- update the kernel on a live\-usb
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B live\-kernel\-updater
[\fIoptions\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBlive\-kernel\-updater\fR updates the live kernels on a live\-usb
system.  It can add new live kernels, update or remove existing ones.
For a kernel to be live\-bootable it must be present in the squashfs
(linuxfs) image.
.PP
The tool supports two methods of booting a live system:
.TP
\fBShared\-initrd mode\fR
The kernel modules of all live kernels are stored together in one
shared initramfs (\fIinitrd.gz\fR).  Two live kernels are supported:
\fIvmlinuz\fR and \fIvmlinuz1\fR, sharing one \fIinitrd.gz\fR.
.TP
\fBMulti\-kernel mode\fR
Each live kernel \fIvmlinuzN\fR has its own initramfs \fIinitrdN.gz\fR.
Up to ten live kernels are supported (\fIvmlinuz\fR through
\fIvmlinuz9\fR).
.PP
The tool writes a small \fIvmlinuzN.ver\fR version file alongside each
live kernel for use by GRUB menu entries.  Microcode (AMD and Intel)
is automatically added into the initrd via \fBuc\-tool\fR when
available.
.SH BASIC OPERATION
When options do not fully specify what to do, menus are presented at each
step.
.TP
\fBSelect the system to update\fR
If running from a live\-usb the current system is offered first.  Any other
plugged\-in USB devices that contain a live system are also listed.  A
directory path may be given directly via \fB\-\-device\fR to skip this menu.
.TP
\fBSelect an action to perform\fR
Available actions depend on the mode and the state of the live system.
.PP
\fIIn multi\-kernel mode:\fR
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\fBUpdate vmlinuzN from ...\fR \(en replace vmlinuzN with another kernel.
When a kernel not yet assigned to any vmlinuzN is available it appears as
a plain update; otherwise it appears as \fB(reassign)\fR, allowing any
installed kernel to be selected.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBAdd new kernel to vmlinuzN\fR \(en install a kernel into the next free
vmlinuzN
.IP \(bu 2
\fBRemove kernel vmlinuzN\fR \(en remove vmlinuzN and its initrd from the
live\-usb, taking it out of the GRUB boot menu
.RE
.PP
\fIIn shared\-initrd mode:\fR
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\fBUpdate vmlinuz from ...\fR and \fBUpdate vmlinuz1 from ...\fR \(en replace
the kernel in vmlinuz or vmlinuz1 with another installed kernel.  Only
kernels not already assigned to either vmlinuz or vmlinuz1 are offered.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBRollback vmlinuz\fR and \fBRollback vmlinuz1\fR \(en revert to the
previous kernel (only shown after an update has been done)
.IP \(bu 2
\fBUpdate initrd\fR \(en recreate the initrd from scratch using the template
initrd, without changing the kernel.  Useful to pick up initrd changes
independently of a kernel update.
.RE
.PP
The currently running live kernel is marked with \fB*\fR in the menu.
vmlinuzN kernels that were uninstalled under root persistence and may not
boot are marked with \fB?\fR.
.TP
\fBSelect new kernel\fR
When an update or add action is chosen and more than one kernel is available,
a list is presented.  The kernel being replaced is marked with \fB*\fR.
When adding a new vmlinuzN on a running live system, the currently running
kernel is marked with \fB*\fR.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-C\fR, \fB\-\-color=\fR\fIscheme\fR
Set the color scheme.  Valid values: \fBoff\fR, \fBlow\fR, \fBlow1\fR, \fBbw\fR,
\fBdark\fR, \fBhigh\fR.
.TP
\fB\-d\fR, \fB\-\-device=\fR\fIdevice\fR
The live\-usb device to update.  Use \fBlive\fR to explicitly target the running
live system.  A block device path (e.g. \fI/dev/sdb1\fR) causes the tool to
mount and update that device.  A directory path (e.g. \fI/mnt/usb\fR) is used
directly as the live mount point without mounting.
.TP
\fB\-e\fR, \fB\-\-encrypt\fR
Force \fBcryptsetup\fR to be copied into the initrd regardless of whether
the boot environment uses disk encryption.  Useful for testing on
non\-encrypted live systems.
.TP
\fB\-F\fR, \fB\-\-force=\fR\fIlist\fR
Force one or more comma\-separated options:
.RS
.IP "\fBflock\fR" 8
ignore a missing \fBflock\fR program
.IP "\fBusb\fR" 8
allow updating non\-USB devices (dangerous)
.IP "\fBclear\fR" 8
remove the previous initrd working directory before unpacking
.RE
.TP
\fB\-G\fR, \fB\-\-graphic\-ui\fR
Use the interactive terminal menu interface with keyboard navigation.
This is the default.
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Show usage summary and exit.
.TP
\fB\-i\fR, \fB\-\-initrd\fR
Only rebuild the initrd from the default template; do not change the
kernel.  Uses \fI/usr/lib/iso\-template/template\-initrd.gz\fR or
\fI/usr/local/lib/iso\-template/template\-initrd.gz\fR.  Shared\-initrd
mode only; not supported in multi\-kernel mode.
.TP
\fB\-\-initrd=\fR\fIfile\fR
In shared\-initrd mode: rebuild the initrd using \fIfile\fR as the
template instead of the default; do not change the kernel.
In multi\-kernel mode: use \fIfile\fR as the template initrd for the
selected vmlinuzN slot instead of the default template.  The normal
slot\-selection menu is shown; kernel modules for the chosen kernel
are installed into the per\-slot initrdN.gz as usual.
Any modules already present in \fIfile\fR are removed before the new
kernel modules are added, so any existing initrd or backup copy can
be used as the template.
.TP
\fB\-I\fR, \fB\-\-ignore\-config\fR
Do not read the configuration file.
.TP
\fB\-k\fR, \fB\-\-kernel=\fR\fIversion\fR
Select the new kernel by version string (as reported by \fBuname \-r\fR).
Skips the kernel selection menu.  Shared\-initrd mode only; not supported
in multi\-kernel mode.
.TP
\fB\-K\fR, \fB\-\-keep\-old\fR
Keep the old kernel module directory inside the initrd instead of removing it.
Shared\-initrd mode only.
.TP
\fB\-\-live\-dir=\fR\fIdir\fR
Specify the subdirectory within the live\-usb that holds the boot files
(e.g. \fBantiX\fR or \fBantiXFrugal\fR).  Skips the automatic search and any
interactive prompt when multiple live directories are found.
.TP
\fB\-m\fR, \fB\-\-modules=\fR\fIlist\fR
Add the listed comma\-separated kernel modules to the initrd.
In shared\-initrd mode the listed modules are added to the existing
initrd.gz without rebuilding it from the template.
In multi\-kernel mode the listed modules are added in addition to the
standard kernel modules during a normal vmlinuzN update.
.TP
\fB\-\-multi\-kernel\fR
Force multi\-kernel mode.  Auto\-detected as the default on MX Linux.
.TP
\fB\-N\fR, \fB\-\-numeric\-ui\fR
Use the legacy numbered\-list menu interface instead of the interactive one.
.TP
\fB\-U\fR, \fB\-\-no\-ucode\fR
Skip microcode injection when repacking the initrd.
.TP
\fB\-p\fR, \fB\-\-pretend\fR
Dry\-run mode.  Show what would be done without writing any files.
.TP
\fB\-q\fR, \fB\-\-quiet\fR
Print less output.
.TP
\fB\-R\fR, \fB\-\-reset\-config\fR
Write a configuration template with all entries commented out and exit.
Useful as a starting point for customisation.
.TP
\fB\-\-shared\-initrd\fR
Force shared\-initrd mode.  Used as the default when multi\-kernel mode
is not auto\-detected.
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Show version information and exit.
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB\-\-verbose\fR
Print more output, including the output of sub\-commands.
.TP
\fB\-VV\fR, \fB\-\-very\-verbose\fR
Also print each command before it is run.
.TP
\fB\-W\fR, \fB\-\-write\-config\fR
Write a configuration template with all entries commented out and exit.
Identical in effect to \fB\-\-reset\-config\fR.
.SH FILES
.TP
\fI/etc/live\-kernel\-updater/live\-kernel\-updater.conf\fR
Configuration file.  Sourced as a shell snippet if present.  Created
automatically with defaults on first run.  Use \fB\-\-reset\-config\fR or
\fB\-\-write\-config\fR to write a fresh commented template.
.TP
\fI/usr/lib/iso\-template/template\-initrd.gz\fR
Default initrd template used when rebuilding the initrd.  Falls back to
\fI/usr/lib/iso\-template/initrd.gz\fR if not found.  When
targeting an external USB the template inside the squashfs image is
preferred to ensure the correct distro version is used.
.TP
\fI/etc/live/config/persist\-root\fR
Flag file written by the live init when root persistence is active.
Used by the tool to detect whether vmlinuzN kernels may be affected by
packages uninstalled under persistence.
